---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TravelAffiliateBox from '../components/TravelAffiliateBox.astro';

const PUB_DATE = '2026-05-04';
const travelDestinations = [
  {
    name: 'Odawara Castle',
    description: 'A major castle site for understanding the Hōjō, Toyotomi Hideyoshi, and the final stage of Sengoku unification.',
    placeHref: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Odawara%20Castle',
    stayHref: 'https://www.booking.com/searchresults.html?ss=Odawara%2C%20Kanagawa%2C%20Japan',
  },
  {
    name: 'Sekigahara Battlefield',
    description: 'The battlefield most closely tied to Tokugawa Ieyasu and the political end of the Sengoku period.',
    placeHref: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Sekigahara%20Battlefield',
    stayHref: 'https://www.booking.com/searchresults.html?ss=Sekigahara%2C%20Gifu%2C%20Japan',
  },
  {
    name: 'Azuchi Castle ruins',
    description: 'A strong travel link for Oda Nobunaga, castle innovation, and the transition toward national unification.',
    placeHref: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Azuchi%20Castle%20Ruins',
    stayHref: 'https://www.booking.com/searchresults.html?ss=Omihachiman%2C%20Shiga%2C%20Japan',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Sengoku Period: Japan's Century of War"
  description="A pillar guide to Japan's Sengoku period (1467–1603) — the warlords, the sieges, the unification, and the end of the samurai world's first chapter."
  type="article"
>
  <ArticleSchema
    slot="head"
    headline="The Sengoku Period: Japan's Century of War"
    description="A pillar guide to Japan's Sengoku period (1467–1603) — the warlords, the sieges, the unification, and the end of the samurai world's first chapter."
    datePublished={PUB_DATE}
  />

  <h1>The Sengoku Period: Japan's Century of War</h1>

  <p>
    For roughly 150 years — from 1467 to 1603 — the Japanese archipelago was
    ruled by no one. Warlords called <em>daimyō</em> fought, betrayed, and
    married each other into a slow consolidation that ended with one man
    holding the country: Tokugawa Ieyasu.
  </p>

  <p>
    This page is the entry point for our Sengoku coverage. It gives readers a
    map of the themes this archive will return to: unification, castles,
    firearms, battlefield geography, and the political road to Tokugawa rule.
  </p>

  <h2>Core questions in this archive</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The Sengoku Period Explained: Japan's Age of Warring States</li>
    <li>Oda Nobunaga Explained: The Warlord Who Changed Japan</li>
    <li>Toyotomi Hideyoshi Explained: From Foot Soldier to Ruler of Japan</li>
    <li>Tokugawa Ieyasu and Sekigahara: The Battle That Made Tokugawa Japan</li>
    <li>Did Samurai Really Use Guns? Sengoku's Forgotten Firearms</li>
    <li>Were Ninjas Real? Shinobi Beyond the Black Costume</li>
  </ul>

  <TravelAffiliateBox
    destinations={travelDestinations}
    title="Sengoku places to understand the period"
    intro="For readers planning a history-focused trip, these places connect directly to major Sengoku castles, battlefields, and warlords."
  />
</BaseLayout>
